The WASP-83 Exoplanetary System


Overview

WASP-83 is a star with 1.11 times the mass of the Sun, and 1.05 times its radius. It is located 884.22 light years away from the solar system and is estimated to be 5 billion years old, as compared to the Sun which is roughly 4.6 billion years old.

WASP-83 is known to have 1 exoplanets in orbit around it.


Exoplanets in the WASP-83 system


WASP-83 b

WASP-83 b was discovered by the SuperWASP observatory, in 2015-07, using the transit method. Its semi-major axis is 0.06 astronomical units, as compared to Earth's which is 1 astronomical unit. The mass of WASP-83 b is 95.400 times the mass of Earth. The radius of WASP-83 b is 11.657 that of Earth. At more than 50 Earth masses, WASP-83 b is a gas giant, a planet whose mass is mostly made up of hydrogen and helium, like Jupiter and Saturn in our solar system.
description: 3D visualisation and gravity simulation of the exoplanet system WASP-83, which contains 1 exoplanets and was discovered by the SuperWASP.
